sky=E2=80=99s the limit. God forbid, but I think the thread bois might star=
t telling us that 97% of us are using nail guns wrong before dropping the 1=
0 big construction projects we missed this week.=C2=A0
Plus, it=E2=80=99s simply good business. Advertisers are dying for more liv=
e stuff, and this would be a particularly local form of entertainment that =
would do well with national and local advertisers alike. We talked about th=
e shine that Wawa (500k+ views) and Starr Restaurants (60k+ views) got for =
providing dinner for the workers, but we haven=E2=80=99t yet talked about t=
he fact that Buckley, the construction company hired to do the rebuild, put=
 its signs everywhere at the site in order to take advantage of all the eye=
balls on the livestream.=C2=A0
Advertisers would be tripping over themselves to get involved. They=E2=80=
=99d start paying for the privilege of providing tradespeople with free foo=
d. A shot of McConkle eating your restaurant=E2=80=99s chicken parm would f=
ill your Resy for weeks. For the big, national projects, next to the Buckle=
y signs, there would be billboards for Bud Light (with a disclaimer to neve=
r drink and build, of course), Clorox (gotta get those hard-earned stains o=
ut), Amazon, Visa, homebuilders, banks, energy utilities, you name it. But =
smaller, local projects would be supported by smaller, local businesses, al=
l tripping over each other to take a little bit of credit for bringing clea=
n energy to your house, shortening your commute, or lowering your rent.=C2=
=A0
Where would all that money go?=C2=A0
Some of it would go to cover the cost of the projects, making the financial=
 case for building even more attractive to developers.=C2=A0
Some of it might go to the campaigns of the local politicians who pushed ap=
provals through =E2=80=93 all done transparently and openly in accordance w=
ith campaign finance rules, of course =E2=80=93 making it electorally suici=
dal to stand in the way of projects with popular support.=C2=A0
Some of it should definitely go to the would-be-NIMBY=E2=80=99s to pay them=
 off for getting out of the way of progress. You think this new apartment b=
uilding might hurt the value of your home in a decade when you sell it? Coo=
l cool, here=E2=80=99s $10k right now.=C2=A0
Some of it would go to the workers themselves. Each project would split its=
 ad revenue with the tradespeople, letting the biggest, most important proj=
ects attract the very best talent. The best tradespeople could negotiate th=
eir own sponsorship deals, too. Like Nascar drivers, they=E2=80=99d rock sh=
irts full of logos. Like golfers, they=E2=80=99d get paid to only use a cer=
tain brand of tools. Sponsors would fly them private from big project to bi=
g project as their particular brand of expertise was needed to solve a part=
icularly hard challenge. Of course, they could do TikToks and Tweets and In=
stas and good ol=E2=80=99 fashioned linear commercials, too.=C2=A0
The money and fame, and the fact that building shit is cool again, would he=
lp solve the labor shortage. Kids would dream of becoming tradespeople inst=
ead of sitting at computer screens all day.=C2=A0
Call me a dreamer, but it just might help solve immigration, too, as fans o=
f local construction projects would get sick and tired of losing out to bet=
ter-resourced rivals because of a lack of talent. They=E2=80=99d demand imm=
igration reform in order to recruit the hungry workers from around the worl=
d who would kill for a chance to move to Durham, North Carolina for their s=
hot at fame and fortune. I=E2=80=99ve yet to hear of a talented basketball =
player who couldn=E2=80=99t make it to the NBA because of visa issues.=C2=
=A0
What about unions? Glad you asked. The Philly plan strikes the perfect bala=
nce of working with unions to get tradespeople paid what they deserve with =
the public scrutiny that would prevent the excess that has crept into the s=
ystem. Hand to god, a friend whose family owns a construction business in P=
hilly told me that they had to pay a guy full wages to turn on the lights i=
n the morning, get drunk all day, and turn the lights off at night. That sh=
it=E2=80=99s not gonna fly when thousands of fans are rooting to stay on bu=
dget, but those same fans are going to heckle developers into paying up for=
 the very best people when they deserve it. Problem solved, next.=C2=A0
If you think this plan is stupid, that there=E2=80=99s not enough attention=
 and money to go around, let me introduce you to the internet, where thousa=
nds of people live-dunked on five people dying in a submarine, where thousa=
nds more sat glued to their screens watching an aborted Russian coup over t=
he weekend, where 140 million people watch other people play video games on=
 Twitch every month, a number dwarfed by YouTube=E2=80=99s 2.68 billion mon=
thly users. And don=E2=80=99t get me started on political news networks and=
 internet commentary. There is so much energy on the internet directed at s=
o much dumb shit; I promise you, if we tap into even a moderate amount of t=
hat, we=E2=80=99ll get the eyeballs.=C2=A0
And as for the money? The money=E2=80=99s actually not the problem. As Noah=
 Smith wrote in The Build-Nothing Country:
For decades, I=E2=80=99ve heard progressives, including my friends and rela=
tives, bemoan America=E2=80=99s unwillingness to spend money on things like=
 transit and green energy. But now America is spending all the money, and t=
hings still aren=E2=80=99t getting built, because of the country=E2=80=99s =
broken system of permitting, land use, and development.=C2=A0
We could certainly spend a few dozen million of the trillions of dollars ea=
rmarked for building stuff on generating the popular support necessary to a=
ctually build stuff.=C2=A0
That leaves the =E2=80=9Ccountry=E2=80=99s broken system of permitting, lan=
d use, and development,=E2=80=9D which, and again if you=E2=80=99re looking=
 for nuance and actual policy expertise you=E2=80=99re in the wrong place, =
seems like a pretty easy set of dominoes to topple at this point in the arg=
ument.=C2=A0
Say you=E2=80=99re running for City Council in a city, and your track recor=
d and platform is blocking stuff. You tell people, =E2=80=9CIf elected, I w=
ill make sure that our city=E2=80=99s commitment to the full environmental =
review process never wavers.=E2=80=9D In the past, you might have gotten aw=
ay with this, because the only people closely watching the City Council ele=
ction are exactly the people who want to ensure that the city=E2=80=99s com=
mitment to the full environmental review process never wavers. But now, loc=
al elections are like the NBA Draft, or to use an analogy that doesn=E2=80=
=99t actually happen, like letting fans vote on who owns their favorite tea=
m. Making that kind of anti-building statement would be like stumping for P=
hiladelphia City Council election with the slogan, =E2=80=9CFuck the Eagles=
=2E=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99d get like seven votes.=C2=A0
You can apply a similar logic up and down the stack, from small local elect=
ions, to Mayoral and Gubernatorial elections, and even national elections. =
If we can get people to feel the same pride in their hometown=E2=80=99s abi=
lity to build as they do for their hometown sports teams, then running on a=
nything but a pro-building platform would be political suicide.=C2=A0
Then, as Governor Shapiro showed, once pro-building representatives are in =
office, they can take the celebrity and popularity they gain from completin=
g big projects quickly and share it with all of the people who helped make =
it happen. The sharer=E2=80=99s popularity with those folks =E2=80=93 the u=
nions, mayors, administrators, and companies needed to get things done =E2=
=80=93 would grow, and the popularity of the folks with whom praise has bee=
n shared would grow, too. The incentive would flip from blocking stuff to g=
etting stuff built. Laws would change and permitting would be reformed, lik=
e it has been in many red states.=C2=A0
If anything, things would flip too far in the other direction, with politic=
ians racing to cut reviews out of the process. That=E2=80=99s a future prob=
lem. Right now, our goal is to figure out how to end the decades-long build=
ing stalemate that ails the country. Too far is fine for now.=C2=A0
This post started out as kind of a joke, but the more I think about it, the=
 more I like the plan. It may just be dumb enough to work.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re living in a world in which billionaires are challenging each =
other to fights on social media. People endlessly debate the superiority of=
 various cities online. Any tweet with pictures of beautiful architecture a=
nd rueful claims that we can=E2=80=99t build like that anymore goes viral.=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CBut this is different,=E2=80=9D you say. =E2=80=9CThis is politics=
! This isn=E2=80=99t how things work in politics!=E2=80=9D=20
Oh really? Obama won in 2008 in large part by being the first candidate to =
embrace social media. Trump won in 2016 by turning the presidential race in=
to a reality TV show. This cycle, we=E2=80=99ve even gotten sporty. Miami M=
ayor Francis Suarez announced his candidacy with a video of him running and=
 playing soccer [ https://substack.com/redirect/ba7c8ef7-4f56-4d1b-9430-062=
9309a91f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] to show off his vitality. Not to be outdone, RFK Jr. is challenging peo=
ple to debates on Joe Rogan and dropping viral videos of himself benching s=
hirtless in jeans [ https://substack.com/redirect/adf290b9-15b2-4702-adbe-1=
a13ac8df88d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ].=C2=A0
We could bemoan the fact that things have come to this, or we could steal t=
he tricks and channel all of that weird energy into something productive, s=
omething that makes peoples=E2=80=99 everyday lives better.=C2=A0
Most people want to live in a country that builds. They want better roads, =
shorter commutes, cheaper rents, more beautiful buildings, cheaper energy, =
chip factories on our home turf, higher-paying jobs. The current system, al=
ong with a very vocal NIMBY minority, stand in the way of that, and it=E2=
=80=99s proven exceedingly difficult to cut through via normal channels.=C2=
=A0
So fuck it, we build.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s go over the top, embrace the reality of modernity, and do som=
ething useful with it.=C2=A0
Can we restore civic pride, bring back positive politics, fix labor shortag=
es and immigration, and build some big, useful stuff along the way? I think=
 we can.
Will we step on some toes? Yes. Will impassioned fans heckle NIMBYs until t=
hey concede? Probably, but please don=E2=80=99t do that, y=E2=80=99all. Wil=
l there be lawsuits? Hell yeah, there will be lawsuits. In this brave new w=
orld, lawsuits are just another source of televised competition.=C2=A0
It was just 12 days and 140 feet of road, but Pennsylvania=E2=80=99s abilit=
y to rebuild I-95 showed those of us who are looking that there=E2=80=99s a=
 better way. It=E2=80=99s something to=E2=80=A6 build on.=C2=A0
Anyway, that=E2=80=99s what I=E2=80=99d do. Hammer=E2=80=99s in your court,=
 Mayor Pete.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/07a6e789-2460-412e-84d7-1164e=
42bdab3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], Puja [ https://substack.com/redirect/603e524c-0273-4a1f-a3bc-122b6507874=
e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and=
 Holyn [ https://substack.com/redirect/2848b363-b53c-4694-9b7e-0a7b3ffa8cbf=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for f=
eedback!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 for the Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

